==Higher education== Occupy movements have taken place on college campuses across the United States. [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/10/occupy-uc-berkeley-police_n_1086195.html |title=Occupy U.C. Berkeley Protesters Face Violent Confrontation With Campus Police (VIDEO) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> [[San Francisco State University]], [[University of California, Irvine|UC Irvine]],<ref name="Occupy Takes Over UCI>["http://www.newuniversity.org/2011/11/news/23976/] 8 November 2011. Retrieved 10 November 2011. </ref> and [[Harvard University]]<ref name="Occupy Harvard">{{cite web|last=Press |first=Associated |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/regional/view/20111110occupy_harvard_students_pitch_tents_in_harvard_yard/srvc=home&position=recent |title=Occupy Harvard: Students pitch tents in Harvard Yard |publisher=BostonHerald.com |date=2011-11-10 |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> are some institutions of higher education that have held occupations in support of the Occupy movement. [[Occupy Texas State]] at [[Texas State University]] is one of the first to form amount{{What|date=November 2011}} universities and colleges in Texas and is one of the largest with fifty dedicated members. At [[Saint Mary's College of California]], held teach-ins to educate students on the Occupy movement and encourage them to get involved.<ref name="Occupy SMC">{{cite news| url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/ci_19256870?IADID=Search-www.contracostatimes.com-www.contracostatimes.com| date=3 November 2011| accessdate= 10 November 2011|title=Saint Mary's joins 'Occupy Wall Street' movement| author= Jonathan Morales| work=Contra Costa Times}}</ref>
==Public opinion polls== An October 12â16 poll found that 67% of New York City voters agreed with the protesters and 87% believed that they had a right to protest.<ref name="reuters17thpoll">Reuters (October 17, 2011) [http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/17/us-protests-idUSTRE79G55O20111017 "New Yorkers support anti-Wall Street protests: poll"] ''Reuters.com''</ref> A national poll conducted by [[Public Policy Polling]] released on November 16 shows 45% of Americans opposing the movement and 33% favoring it.<ref>[http://dailycaller.com/2011/11/16/poll-45-percent-oppose-the-99-percent/ Poll: 45 percent oppose the â99 percentâ]</ref> A Siena poll of New York released on November 15 shows that two-thirds of New Yorkers do not believe that the movement represents "the 99%". <ref>[http://blogs.buffalonews.com/politics_now/2011/11/siena-poll-good-news-for-obama-occupy-campers.html Buffalo News Siena Poll Good News for Obama and Occupy Campers]</ref>
==Impact on US Politics== US Presidential Candidate [[Buddy Roemer]] made headlines by becoming the first candidate to vocally support the Occupy Movement. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65378.html |title=Buddy Roemer: The Occupy Wall Street candidate? - Alexander Burns |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> <!-- Add other statements from politicians Coburn has one, etc--> [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] presidential candidate [[Carl E. Person]] has also reached out to the movement.<ref>http://occupywallst.org/forum/carl-person-movement-supporter-ignored-running-for/</ref><ref>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOzgUPuJ2mk</ref>
